  "body": "## Preamble\r\n\r\n    VIP: 931\r\n    Title: Modify public variable syntax to decorator\r\n    Author: @fubuloubu\r\n    Type: Standard\r\n    Status: Draft\r\n    Created: 2018-06-24\r\n\r\n\r\n## Simple Summary\r\nChange public getter syntax from:\r\n```python\r\nmyVar: public(type)\r\n```\r\nto\r\n```python\r\n@public\r\nmyVar: type\r\n```\r\nto match decorators on functions and create more consistent style\r\n\r\n## Abstract\r\nWe have two different styles for using the `public` qualifier on functions vs. variables.\r\nThis could be a good thing, but I think it's better to be more consistent in our use of decorators as it will be more auditable.\r\n\r\n## Motivation\r\nI think the following is easier to spot in a contract\r\n```python\r\n@public\r\nmyVar: type\r\n```\r\nI know if I see that decorator, the variable has a public getter.\r\n\r\nCurrent syntax is hard to see if skimming quickly, plus it pollutes the underlying syntax when defining complex types like structs.\r\n\r\n## Specification\r\nNew syntax mentioned above\r\n\r\nMakes it easier to add future variable decorators, if required\r\n\r\n## Backwards Compatibility\r\nNot backwards compatible, user breaking change.\r\n\r\n## Copyright\r\nCopyright and related rights waived via [CC0](https://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/)\r\n",
